node.text:
Almost two decades before cell phone video cameras came into widespread use, the violent actions of N.Y.P.D. officers during the Tompkins Square Park riot in 1988 were caught on a hand-held video camera by local Lower East Side resident and artist Clayton Patterson (@claytonles). In this episode of I Was There, Clayton recounts the wild and free era of the L.E.S. in the 80s and the events that led up to the riot and its aftermath, which included the indictment of several police officers and a jail sentence for Clayton for refusing to turn over his footage to authorities. 

Featuring Excerpts From the Film “CAPTURED” (2008) provided by Clayton Patterson, Elsa Rensaa, Daniel B. Levin, and Ben Solomon. www.capturedmovie.com 

Featuring: @claytonles

node.text:
What happened to the man on fire? In 2017, a single photo brought worldwide attention to the brutality of frontline protests in Venezuela. It was taken by Ronaldo Schemidt. This is the story. 

In Developing News, VICE interviews photographers whose photos have become synonymous with important world events. The photographers relive the story behind the photos, telling their tales from the front line of battlefields and hospitals, and reflecting on their journey to becoming a photographer. 

We hear how they sought out to document the truth, even risking their lives, to provide proof of events that stay long after the memories fade.

#vwn #viceworldnews

node.title: What Happened to the Man on Fire in Venezuela?

node.text:
One of the internet's best-known memes was created by Chris Torres in 2011. Ten years later, he sold it for more than half a million dollars. 

We speak to Chris about the weird new world of non-fungible tokens (NFTs) to understand why people are paying up to millions of dollars for something they can’t physically own.

In Super Users, we go down an internet rabbit hole to hear from people whose lives have become defined by their online presence.

In 2018, photographer Sumy Sadurni embedded with rebel forces in South Sudan to document their fight against government troops during a six-year civil war that ravaged the world’s youngest nation. ⁣
⁣
In Developing News, VICE interviews photographers whose photos have become synonymous with important world events. The photographers relive the story behind the photos, telling their tales from the front line of battlefields and hospitals, and reflecting on their journey to becoming a photographer. ⁣
⁣
We hear how they sought out to document the truth, even risking their lives, to provide proof of events that stay long after the memories fade.⁣

node.text:
The Sidoarjo Mud Flow is an eruption of the world’s largest mud volcano in Porong, Sidoarjo in East Java, Indonesia.

This on-going disaster has been spewing toxic mud since May 2006, displacing thousands of people from their homes, as well as an alarming increase in serious health issues among residents.

The cause of the mudflow has been widely contested with two leading theories. Some believe it was caused by PT Lapindo, a gas & oil company drilling in the region. Others believe it was caused by an earthquake that occurred at the same time as the eruption.

In this episode of “I Was There”, we meet with Harwati, a mudflow survivor who was born and raised in Sidoarjo.

node.title: The Toxic Mud Volcano That Wiped Out Entire Villages | I Was There

node.text:
Almost two decades before cell phone video cameras came into widespread use, the violent actions of N.Y.P.D. officers during the Tompkins Square Park riot in 1988 were caught on a hand-held video camera by local Lower East Side resident and artist Clayton Patterson (@claytonles). In this episode of I Was There, Clayton recounts the wild and free era of the L.E.S. in the 80s and the events that led up to the riot and its aftermath, which included the indictment of several police officers and a jail sentence for Clayton for refusing to turn over his footage to authorities. 

Featuring Excerpts From the Film “CAPTURED” (2008) provided by Clayton Patterson, Elsa Rensaa, Daniel B. Levin, and Ben Solomon. www.capturedmovie.com

Researchers have developed a new method of 3D modeling surface tension and the results are frighteningly realistic.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
The interaction of solids and liquids is hard to accurately simulate, largely due to computational limits. The researchers’ method of creating a separate system that simulates the surface tension that arises around these interactions is a workaround, one the team acknowledges has limitations.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Via @motherboardvice 
Link in bio.
